export const VOLUMES = {"I":{"title":"The great Russian novels, snow, candlelight, and dread","intro":"The nineteenth-century Russian novel lives between the frozen white of the steppe and the gold candlelight of the salon, with the grey of Petersburg stone and the deep red of icon and uniform. Its colour is cold ground warmed only by fire and faith. Each refuses the flag-red 'Soviet' shorthand: these are imperial palettes of snow, beeswax, and incense, not propaganda red."},"II":{"title":"The gothic novels, moonlight, decay, and blood","intro":"Gothic fiction is built on moonlit stone, candle-shadow, mouldering velvet, and the single shock of blood. The palette is cold and dark, punctuated by fire and crimson, with the texture of decay. Each refuses the cartoon Halloween orange-and-black: literary gothic is a subtle range of moon-grey, bruise, and oxblood."},"III":{"title":"The modernist city, grey stone and electric dawn","intro":"Modernist fiction maps the early-twentieth-century city — London, Dublin, New York — in its specific weather and light: Thames fog, Dublin stone, Jazz-Age glitter. The palettes are urban, atmospheric, and tuned to a single day's hours. Each refuses the generic 'vintage' sepia: each modernist city has a precise, particular colour."},"IV":{"title":"The magical-real, heat, dust, and impossible colour","intro":"Magical realism saturates the everyday — Latin American heat, tropical bloom, and dust given the intensity of the marvellous. The palettes are warm, earthen, and lit by one impossible hue that signals the magic seeping in. Each refuses the flat 'exotic' brights: the colour is grounded in real heat and clay, with the marvellous as a single saturated note."},"V":{"title":"The Japanese page, restraint, snow, and one accent","intro":"Japanese literature, from Heian court to postwar, favours restraint and the single resonant accent — indigo and ink with one note of red or gold, or the white of snow against a lacquer dark. The palettes are quiet, seasonal, and exact. Each refuses the busy 'Japan brights' of tourism: these are spare, tonal palettes built around one deliberate colour."},"VI":{"title":"The American South, heat, dust, and faded grandeur","intro":"Southern Gothic lives in heat-hazed greens, red clay, weathered white clapboard, and the deep shade of a porch. The palette is humid, sun-faded, and overgrown, with decay always at the edge. Each refuses the pretty plantation-romance gloss: this is a South of dust, kudzu, and peeling paint."},"VII":{"title":"Imagined tyrannies, grey states and one warning colour","intro":"Literary dystopia drains colour to signal control: institutional grey, propaganda red, and sterile white, with any warmth coming as forbidden contraband. The palette is regimented, with a single charged accent. Each refuses a neutral 'futuristic' look: dystopia is a deliberate near-monochrome broken by the colour of the regime or the resistance."},"VIII":{"title":"The illustrated page, ink, watercolour, and wonder","intro":"Children's classics are remembered through their illustration — Tenniel's engraving, Shepard's pencil, Sendak's crosshatch, watercolour wash. The palettes come from the printed page: warm paper, ink line, and gentle colour. Each refuses the plastic toy-brights of modern merchandise: these are the soft, printed palettes of the original books."},"IX":{"title":"Mid-century America, highway, neon, and grain","intro":"The Beats and their mid-century contemporaries wrote a America of desert highway, diner neon, and tobacco-stained interiors — warm, restless, and a little worn. The palettes are road-dusty and lamplit. Each refuses the clean retro-Americana of nostalgia branding: this is the grainy, smoke-stained version, not the diner-mug pastiche."},"X":{"title":"Invented worlds, mapped in earth and weather","intro":"Epic fantasy builds its worlds in elemental colour — the green Shire, the grey of a northern wall, the gold of an old empire. The palettes are landscape-led, each realm a distinct climate and material culture. Each refuses the generic 'medieval' brown-grey murk: each invented land has a specific, grounded palette."},"XI":{"title":"The southern sun, stucco, sea, and dust","intro":"The literature of Spain, Italy, and the Mediterranean is lit by hard southern sun on stucco, terracotta, and dust, with the deep blue of the sea and the black of mourning dress. The palettes are warm, faded, and sun-struck. Each refuses the tourism-poster cobalt-and-white: these are lived-in southern palettes of dust, ochre, and shade."},"XII":{"title":"The Victorian city, fog, gaslight, and soot","intro":"The Victorian novel's London is fog, soot, gaslight, and the deep colours of a respectable interior — bottle green, oxblood, and brass against perpetual grey. The palette is dim, warm-lamped, and coal-stained. Each refuses the cheery 'Dickensian Christmas-card' brights: this London is a sooty, gaslit grey warmed only by fire and lamp."}};
